Meanwhile — content and usage notice
=======================================

WHAT THIS TOOL IS
-----------------
Meanwhile is a *headline aggregator*. It reads publicly syndicated feeds and
public, key-free APIs that are explicitly designed for programmatic access, and
shows a clustered daily digest of what is being published about AI/tech.

For each item it stores and displays ONLY:
  - the title
  - the source/publisher name
  - the publication date
  - a SHORT extract (≈700 characters max) taken from the summary the source
    itself publishes in its feed
  - the canonical link to the original article

It NEVER fetches, stores, or displays the article body or `content:encoded`.
The link always points back to the publisher.

SOURCES (PRIMARY ONLY)
----------------------
Content is fetched only from PRIMARY sources — first-party lab blogs, reputable
press, and individual technical authors — never from aggregators or curated
newsletters (re-summarizing those is a copyright-risk zone). Specifically:
  - RSS / Atom feeds published by the source for syndication
  - the arXiv API (export.arxiv.org) — public, no key
  - release/changelog Atom feeds (GitHub releases.atom) — public, no key
  (The Hacker News Search API is supported but disabled by default: it carries
   no syndicated summary to work from.)

Fetching is rate-limited to at most once per day (lazy cache). Requests send a
descriptive User-Agent. On HTTP 403/429 the tool backs off and skips the source
rather than retrying aggressively. No paywalled content is accessed, and no
scraping beyond the feeds/APIs above is performed.

AI SUMMARIES (DIGEST ONLY, FROM THE RSS EXTRACT)
------------------------------------------------
For news (DIGEST) items, the tool may rewrite the SHORT RSS extract into a fresh
3-to-5-sentence summary using a hosted LLM. A provider chain is tried in order, all on
free tiers: Google's Gemini (flash-lite), then Groq, then Cerebras. This is done
legally-by-design:
  - The ONLY input to the model is the publisher's own syndicated extract — never
    the article body, never scraped page content.
  - The model is asked to rewrite the facts in NEW words; the original phrasing is
    not reproduced.
  - Every summarized item STILL shows its source name and a link back to the
    original article. The summary supplements attribution; it never replaces it.
  - RELEASE (changelog) items and LEARN (evergreen concepts) are NOT summarized.
  - Each provider's API key (GEMINI_API_KEY / GROQ_API_KEY / CEREBRAS_API_KEY) is
    read only from the environment; it is never stored, written to disk, or
    committed. With no keys, or once every provider hits its quota, the tool falls
    back to showing the original RSS extract.
  - Summaries are clearly LABELED as AI-generated (a "↻ AI summary" marker) so they
    are never presented as human-written journalism, and may contain errors — they
    supplement the linked original, which stays canonical.
  - Each provider's terms permit using and redistributing model outputs. Via Groq or
    Cerebras the summary may be produced by an open Llama-family model; outputs are
    redistributed subject to that model's license. (Gemini's free tier may use
    submitted content to improve Google's products — the only input is already-public
    RSS snippets, never private data.)

CENTRAL FEED (REDISTRIBUTION)
-----------------------------
By default, clients do not summarize locally: a maintainer builds the digest once
a day and publishes a small JSON (titles, short syndicated extracts, the rewritten
summaries, and links) that clients pull. This redistributes short, attributed
snippets plus original summaries — never article bodies — each item linking back to
its publisher. Only primary sources are included. A publisher who wishes to be
excluded can be removed from data/feeds.txt; on request, remove the feed and
rebuild. Anyone may instead run their own feed (their own key) and point clients at
it via NEWS_FEED_URL.

ATTRIBUTION AND OWNERSHIP
-------------------------
All titles, extracts, and links remain the property of their respective
publishers and authors. Every item is shown WITH its source name and a link back
to the original. This tool claims no ownership over any aggregated content; any
AI summary it adds is derived solely from the publisher's syndicated extract and
is always accompanied by attribution and a link.

TAKEDOWN / REMOVAL REQUESTS
---------------------------
If you are a publisher or rights holder and want your source excluded, open an
issue on the project's GitHub repository with the label "takedown":
  https://github.com/riccardomusumeci11/meanwhile/issues
Requests are honored promptly and in good faith: the feed is removed from
data/feeds.txt, the central feed is rebuilt, and the source no longer appears. No
justification is required. Every item already links back to your original article
and shows your name; this project claims no ownership over any aggregated content.

